that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected;

-Safety emergency response procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a release - including annual training;

-State-of-the-art building enclosures around chlorine and phosgene equipment to contain a leak and prevent the leak from reaching the atmosphere;

-Dedicated scrubbing systems that destroy chlorine or phosgene gas from process vent systems and in the event of an emergency release from the manufacturing process;

-Transfer of chlorine and phosgene liquid is done within a double-walled or pipe-within-a-pipe system to minimize the risk of leaks to the atmosphere;

-Phosgene and chlorine gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;

-Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;

-Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions;

-Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistent safe work practices;

-Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability - including equipment testing and inspection;

-A safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications for possible hazards before they are implemented (this is called Management of Change);

-Safety pre-qualification for all contractors;

-Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and,

-Safety permitting procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding and other maintenance activities.

0.5 FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY

There have been no RMP-related incidents at the Burkville facility during the previous five-year period.

